## Problem
The SearchBar dropdown in FinanceModule does not properly announce search results to screen readers and lacks clear keyboard navigation escape paths. When search results appear, users are not informed of result count or how to navigate results.

## Evidence
- `src/renderer/src/modules/finance/home/SearchBar.tsx:60-83` — Dropdown list renders without `role="listbox"` or `role="option"` on children. No `aria-live="polite"` region to announce results
- Line 52-54: Escape key closes dropdown but no feedback for screen reader users
- No `aria-expanded` or `aria-controls` to link input to results
- Lines 67-80: Result buttons lack semantic markup; they should be `role="option"` children of a `role="listbox"`

## Expected
- Dropdown should have `role="listbox"` with `aria-label="Search results"`
- Each result should be `role="option"` with proper ARIA attributes
- Input should have `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls`, and `aria-owns` to connect to results
- A live region (`aria-live="polite"`) should announce result count when dropdown opens

## Proposed fix
```tsx
// Before
<div
  className={cn(
    'absolute bottom-12 left-0 right-0 z-20 max-h-80 overflow-y-auto rounded-md border',
    'border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-bg-elev)]'
  )}
>
  {results.map((r) => (
    <button key={r.symbol} onClick={() => go(r.symbol)} ...>
      {r.symbol}
    </button>
  ))}
</div>

// After
<div
  className={cn(...)} 
  role="listbox"
  aria-label="Search results"
  aria-live="polite"
>
  {results.length === 0 && (
    <div role="status" aria-live="polite">No results found</div>
  )}
  {results.map((r, i) => (
    <button
      key={r.symbol}
      role="option"
      aria-selected={i === selectedIdx}
      onClick={() => go(r.symbol)}
      ...>
      {r.symbol}
    </button>
  ))}
</div>
```

## Impact
Screen reader users cannot discover search results or navigate them efficiently. This breaks a core feature of the application.

## Related
WCAG 2.1 SC 1.3.1 (Semantic Structure), SC 4.1.2 (ARIA State and Properties).

## Problem
The Launchpad home page animates tile entrance and hover effects without respecting the `prefers-reduced-motion` media query. Users with vestibular disorders or motion sensitivity experience disorienting effects.

## Evidence
- `src/renderer/src/styles/globals.css:94-107` — Tile animations use `transform` and `box-shadow` transitions:
  ```css
  .launchpad-tile {
    transition: transform 180ms ..., box-shadow 220ms ..., background 160ms ...;
    animation: lp-tile-in 260ms ...
  }
  .launchpad-tile:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px) scale(1.03);
  }
  ```
- No `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` override
- `src/renderer/src/shell/LaunchpadHome.tsx:516-521` — Tile focus uses border and ring effects that may also feel animated

## Expected
Add to `globals.css`:
```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .launchpad-tile {
    animation: none;
    transition: none;
  }
  .launchpad-tile:hover {
    transform: none;
  }
  * {
    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;
    animation-iteration-count: 1 !important;
    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;
  }
}
```

## Proposed fix
For all CSS transitions and animations:
1. Wrap in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` with `transition: none` or very short durations
2. Set `animation: none` to disable entrance animations
3. Test with macOS Accessibility > Display > Reduce motion enabled

## Impact
Users with motion sensitivity experience dizziness, nausea, or seizure triggers. This is a serious accessibility barrier for a segment of users.

## Related
WCAG 2.1 SC 2.3.3 (Animation from Interactions).

## Problem
The DetailTabs component displays keyboard shortcuts (1-11) in visual <kbd> badges but does not announce them via ARIA. Screen reader users see no hint that number keys activate tabs.

## Evidence
- `src/renderer/src/modules/finance/detail/DetailTabs.tsx:28-45` — Each tab button renders:
  ```tsx
  <button ... title={`${t} (press ${i + 1})`} aria-label={t}>
    {t}
    <kbd>{i + 1}</kbd>
  </button>
  ```
- The `title` attribute is inconsistent (sometimes shows keyboard hint, sometimes not)
- The `aria-label` is just the tab name ("Overview", etc.) and doesn't mention the shortcut
- The <kbd> element is visual-only; screen readers may skip or mispronounce it

## Expected
- `aria-label` should include the keyboard shortcut: "Overview, press 1"
- Or use `aria-describedby` to link to a description of the shortcut
- The <kbd> rendering should be consistent and perhaps use `aria-label` on the badge itself

## Proposed fix
```tsx
// Before
<button
  key={t}
  onClick={() => onChange(t)}
  title={`${t} (press ${i + 1})`}
  aria-label={t}
  className={...}
>
  {t}
  <kbd className={...}>{i + 1}</kbd>
</button>

// After
<button
  key={t}
  onClick={() => onChange(t)}
  aria-label={`${t}, keyboard shortcut ${i + 1}`}
  className={...}
>
  {t}
  <kbd 
    aria-hidden="true"
    className={...}
  >
    {i + 1}
  </kbd>
</button>
```

## Impact
Screen reader users miss an important keyboard navigation feature, reducing efficiency when switching tabs.

## Related
WCAG 2.1 SC 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships), SC 2.1.1 (Keyboard).
